[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/47gAGm9l/jGKO7pIs"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[UTCDate "2021.01.21"]
[UTCTime "12:26:28"]

{ Now for a more advanced example of what can happen if you lose your sense of danger in the opening. }
1. e4 { We already talked about the moves up to 3.Bc4 in the game 'Fast Development In Action'. } 1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Do you remember the name of this opening?
That's right, it is the Italian Game - the most common opening at the beginner and junior levels. } 3... Nf6 { Black develops his knight while attacking the e4-pawn. This is known as the 'Two Knights Defence', however to play it successfully, Black must be prepared to sacrifice a pawn out of the opening. } (3... Bc5 { We already saw this move in 'Fast Development In Action'. } { [%cal Gd8g5,Gf3g5] }) 4. Ng5 { White exploits the one disadvantage of 3...Nf6.
You may remember that the f2 and f7-pawns are the weakest pawns at the start of the game, because they are only defended by the king.
If Black had already developed his f8-bishop, this attack would not achieve anything for White, due to the reply of castling kingside. } 4... d5 { Only this pawn move blocks the threat of Nxf7, forking the d8-queen and h8-rook (see the 4...h6 note). } (4... h6 5. Nxf7 Qe7 6. Nxh8 { White is up a rook and pawn - a decisive material advantage. }) 5. exd5 { White captures the pawn. In doing so, he also defends his bishop from attack. } 5... Nxd5 { What could be more natural than recapturing the pawn?
However, this move is very dangerous for Black, because it re-opens the c4-bishop's diagonal, allowing White to pile up heavy pressure against the 'weakest link' on f7 before Black has castled his king to safety.
To see how Black should play instead, check the 5...Na5 note. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gc4f7] } (5... Na5 { Advanced - This is the correct move, known as 'Polerio's Counterattack'. The idea is to eliminate or distract the c4-bishop, avoiding the problems on f7 we'll see after 5...Nxd5. } 6. Bb5+ { White gives a check while dealing with the threat to his bishop. This follows the Advanced Principle (creating threats), as Black can't recapture the d5-pawn while his king is in check. } 6... c6 { Black continues attacking White's bishop to continue the fight for the initiative (control of the game). This entails sacrificing a pawn. } 7. dxc6 bxc6 { Once again, Black recaptures with the pawn to keep making threats against White's pieces. } 8. Be2 { There are other retreats for the bishop, but this one is the most natural, keeping the bishop out of the range of any attacks. } 8... h6 { Black forces the White knight to a less active post with this attack. } 9. Nf3 e4 { Black attacks the White knight again, while gaining more space in the centre (central control). } 10. Ne5 Bc5 { Black has excellent compensation for the pawn, because of his lead in development and central space advantage. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gd8d4] }) 6. Nxf7 { This is known as The 'Fried Liver Attack'. It leads to very complicated play, where White sacrifices a piece to drag Black's king into the open centre. } (6. d4 { Advanced - This is known as the 'Lolli Attack' and gives White a safer advantage than 6.Nxf7. However, this falls outside the scope of this Study. }) 6... Kxf7 { Black has no good alternative to accepting the piece sacrifice. Now the king is open to checks. } 7. Qf3+ { This is the correct check, because it attacks the f7-king and d5-knight at once.
(Advanced - this double attack is known as a 'fork', and is one of the most important tactics to master to become a strong chess player). } { [%cal Gf3d5,Gf3f7] } 7... Ke6 { Only this move both gets out of check and defends the d5-knight from being captured for free.
The price Black pays is clear - his king is stuck in the centre on e6, and his knight on d5 is in an unpleasant pin from the c4-bishop. } { [%cal Ge6d5] } 8. Nc3 { White increases the pressure on the 'pinned' d5-knight (which cannot move from attack, as then the e6-king would be in check). } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc3d5] } 8... Nb4 { Black defends the d5-knight, while attacking the c2-pawn (threatening a 'fork' on the king and rook).
The position is very complicated and unclear for humans to play, though it's easier to play White, as it's typically easier to attack than defend well, especially at the amateur level. } *


