[UTCTime "12:26:50"]

{ In this example, we will see White sacrificing a pawn to take control of the game and make it harder for the opponent to follow the basic opening principles successfully.

(Advanced - Sacrificing material in the opening is known as an 'Opening Gambit' or 'Gambit' for short.) }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { White places his other pawn in the centre, not fearing the capture on d4.
This move is known as The Scotch Game. } 3... exd4 { Black captures the pawn to eliminate White's 'dream centre' of pawns on d4 and e4. } 4. Bc4 { This is the Scotch Gambit. Compared to 3.Bc4, White has sacrificed a pawn to open the position and develop his pieces more quickly. } { [%cal Gc1h6,Gd1d8] } (4. Nxd4 { (Advanced - Simply recapturing the pawn is known as The Scotch Game. This is the most common move for White.) } 4... Nxd4 { This does not win the knight, as White can recapture with the queen. } 5. Qxd4 { Previously, I was critical of developing the queen too early, because it can be attacked easily by the opponent's pieces with tempo (see 'King Safety - What To Avoid as an example).
However, Black is not able to easily attack the d4-queen with his knight, as the queen's knight was already traded.
Therefore, White's lead in development and extra central space gives him an advantage. }) 4... Bc5 { Black defends the d4-pawn from capture, asking White to justify his opening gambit. } { [%csl Gd4] } 5. c3 { A strong move, attacking the d4-pawn. This also sets a trap that many thousands of inexperienced players have fallen for.
(Advanced - Let's see if you can do better. What would you play here as Black?) } (5. Nxd4 { We can see that the d4-pawn is safe from capture by looking at the attackers and defenders of the pawn: } 5... Nxd4 6. Qxd4 Bxd4 { and Black is up a full queen at the end of the exchanges. }) 5... dxc3 { The most natural move, accepting the pawn sacrifice to keep a material advantage.
However, this move has a concrete tactical problem, based on two key points:
1. The f7-pawn is only defended by the king.
2. The c5-bishop is undefended (making it vulnerable to forks).
Based on these hints, what move would you play as White here? } (5... Nf6 { is the correct move for Black - see the link at the end of this game for more information. }) 6. Bxf7+ { Well done if you found this intermediate move! White lures the Black king into an exposed position, setting up a strong fork. } (6. Nxc3 d6 { gives Black time to protect his bishop against the Bxf7 tactic and consolidate his position. } { [%csl Gc5,Gd6] }) (6. Qd5 { This is the right idea, but the wrong move order. } { [%csl Ge7] } 6... Qe7 { Black defends the f7-pawn and bishop at once. Next move, Black will play ...Nf6 to kick back the White queen and take control of the game. } { [%csl Gf7,Ge7,Gc5] } 7. Nxc3 Nf6 { [%cal Gf6d5] }) 6... Kxf7 { Black may as well take the bishop, as otherwise he lost a pawn with tempo. } 7. Qd5+ { The point - White forks the Black king and bishop. } { [%cal Gd5f7,Gd5c5] } 7... Ke8 { Black chooses this retreat square, so that Qxc5 does not come with check.
Now the automatic move is to take the bishop on c5 and regain the sacrificed bishop, but White can do even better. } 8. Qh5+ { A useful intermediate check, as Black is forced to either place his king on a worse square, or weaken his kingside with ...g6. } 8... g6 { Now the long diagonal is opened up. } (8... Kf8 9. Qxc5+ { checks the king, meaning Black does not have time to keep the extra pawn with ...cxb2. } 9... d6 10. Qxc3 { White is much better here, as Black's king remains uncastled, and White has more space and slightly faster development to boot. } { [%csl Ge4,Gf8] }) 9. Qxc5 { White has regained his piece and left the Black king stuck in the centre.
But what if Black keeps the extra pawn? } 9... cxb2 { This is a very risky move, as it increases White's lead in development. } 10. Bxb2 { Black must deal with the threat of Bxh8. } { [%cal Gb2h8] } 10... Nf6 { Blocking with the knight.
From here, there are a lot of good moves for White, who has scored extremely well from this position in practice. The simplest is to play } 11. O-O { , realizing that the e4-pawn is 'poisoned' and Black can't take it: } (11. e5 { is tempting too, attacking the knight with tempo, though I prefer castling. }) 11... Nxe4 { Attacking the queen, but this can be punished in several ways. } 12. Re1 { White pins the e4-knight to prevent Nxc5.
In turn, Black's h8-rook and e4-knight are both under attack, and he must lose at least one of these pieces.
To learn more about how to play the Scotch Gambit as White and beat 1.e4 e5 in general, check out my course 'How To Beat 1.e4 e5': https://members.illingworthchessacademy.com/offers/7Uxx2XNM } { [%cal Ge1e8,Gb2h8] } *


