{ Conversely, what's the best way to counter opening gambits by our opponent?

In most cases, gambits by Black will be unsound, due to White's extra tempo for development.

However, some of White's gambits can be quite dangerous if Black is not ready for them - as we saw in the previous game. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 (2. d4 exd4 3. c3 { is the Danish Gambit. It has similar ideas to the 'Goring Gambit' and can actually be met in the same way by Black. }) (2. f4 { This is the King's Gambit. It was played a lot in the 19th century and earlier, but isn't seen as much nowadays, because after } 2... exf4 { , Black is not just up a pawn, but White also has to contend with his weakened kingside and open king, which may be exploited with a check on h4, for example. } { [%cal Gd8h4,Gh4e1] }) 2... Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. c3 { This is the Goring Gambit.
What's the best way to deal with such a gambit?
The critical way is certainly to accept the pawn sacrifice, and fend off the initial attack to eventually win the game with your extra material.
However, another option is to give back material to wrest control of the game from the opponent. } 4... d5 { Black hits back in the centre, exchanging White's central pawn while activating his queen and queen's bishop. } (4... dxc3 5. Nxc3 { White sacrifices a pawn to gain a lead in development, open the position and eliminate Black's central pawn. } 5... Bb4 { and ...d6/...Nf6 is now a solid way for Black to develop and get a good game, though some more good moves are still required.
Note that Black placed the bishop on b4 here, rather than the standard c5 square, to pin White's active knight and also avoid the Bc4xf7 tactics we saw in the previous game. } { [%cal Gd7d6,Gg8f6] }) 5. exd5 { White exchanges pawns to get time for cxd4 next move, regaining the pawn. } 5... Qxd5 { Black's queen is active in the centre, though it can also be a target for attack if Black doesn't keep the momentum. } 6. cxd4 { This d4-pawn is known as an 'Isolated Pawn'. It can't be defended by any of White's other pawns.
However, this pawn is both a weakness and a strength - this d4-pawn is the only pawn in the centre, giving White a space advantage.
The best way for Black to deal with this is to keep developing actively. } { [%csl Gd4] } 6... Bg4 { Black pins the f3-knight, threatening to take on f3 and remove the defender of the d4-pawn.
(The rest of this game falls under 'Advanced') } 7. Be2 { White breaks the pin and also indirectly defends the d4-pawn. } 7... Bb4+ { Black continues to develop with tempo, checking the White king to prevent castling. } (7... Bxf3 { Note that the exchanges don't win material for Black: } 8. Bxf3 Qxd4 { This is a blunder - correct is 8...Qc4, with similar play to the 7...Bb4 variation. } 9. Bxc6+ { White removes the defender of the d4-queen with check. } { [%csl Gd4] } 9... bxc6 10. Qxd4 { Always be wary of these tactics (such as removing the defender) when evaluating exchanges and capturing sequences! }) 8. Nc3 { White blocks the check while developing the knight.
The Black queen can't be captured yet, due to the pin on the knight to the king, but if White gets time to castle next move, the threat to Black's queen would become real. } 8... Bxf3 { Normally a bishop is slightly more valuable than a knight, but in this particular position, an otherwise dubious exchange has a very clever dynamic point. } 9. Bxf3 { White recaptures with the bishop to attack the queen with tempo. } 9... Qc4 { The point. Black exchanged on f3 to deflect White's bishop away from c4, so that Black can keep the White king in the centre (by preventing castling).
Furthermore, the c3-knight is threatened, and the d4-pawn will come under even more pressure after long castling.
The position is still about equal, due to White's 'bishop pair' advantage (he has two bishops to Black's one), but Black's initiative makes his position easier to play. } { [%csl Gc3,Gd4][%cal Gc4f1] } *


[Event "Opening Principles For Under 1600s: Fight For The Initiative - Ruy Lopez"]
