{ The fight for the initiative is not limited to open positions either - it also happens in more closed positions, though not quite as obviously.

So let's see how with an example. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { This is the 'Ruy Lopez' Opening, also known as the 'Spanish'.
Why is this the most common move for White among advanced players?
It's because the Ruy Lopez has one big advantage over the Italian (3.Bc4): White attacks and pins the c6-knight, meaning that Black will, at some point, need to resolve the question of how to keep his e5-pawn safe.
This pressure means that Black's good options are somewhat reduced. } { [%csl Ge5] } 3... Nf6 { The Berlin Defence. Black develops his knight and attacks the e4-pawn. } (3... d6 { This move defends the e5-pawn for now, but turns the pin on the c6-knight into an 'absolute pin' - the c6-knight cannot legally move, as then the e8-king would be in check. } 4. d4 { White increases the pressure on the e5-pawn, forcing Black to deal with the threat in some way. We can see how White is taking control of the game with his 'focus fire' strategy against the e5 strongpoint. } { [%csl Ge5] } 4... exd4 { Black exchanges the pawn, sick of the pressure from White's pieces. } 5. Nxd4 { White has more space in the centre and more active pieces. He has good control of the game too. White keeps an initiative, as evidenced by the new threat to the c6-knight (attacked twice and defended only once). } { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gd4c6,Gb5c6] }) (3... a6 { This, the Morphy Defence, is the most common move for Black. The idea of this attack is that the 'threat' to the e5-pawn is not real just yet, as the following variation shows: } 4. Bxc6 { The 'Exchange Spanish'. White doubles Black's pawns, at the price of giving up the bishop pair. } (4. Ba4 { is my recommendation, but this falls outside the scope of our Study. }) 4... dxc6 { Black recaptures away from the centre, so that he can develop his queenside more rapidly and have more mobility for his queen. } { [%cal Gc8g4,Gd8d1] } 5. Nxe5 { This pawn grab is a mistake, because White will not be able to keep the extra pawn. He should have castled instead. } 5... Qd4 { Black regains the pawn with a simple fork. } 6. Nf3 Qxe4+ { Black's position is preferable here, as he has a strong bishop pair on an open board, whereas the doubled pawns on the c-file can't really be exploited by White. } { [%csl Gc8,Gf8] }) 4. O-O { White ignores the attack on the e4-pawn and castles to complete kingside development. That's because he realizes that Black will not be able to hang on to the extra pawn in any case. } 4... Nxe4 { Black may as well take the pawn, as that was the main idea behind 3...Nf6 and not doing so would be inconsistent. } 5. d4 { White ignores the knight to open up the centre and increase his lead in development. We will see in this example that trying to hang on to the extra material as Black only leads to problems. } (5. Re1 { This is a fine move as well, though Black can defend against this early e-file attack. } 5... Nd6 { Black defends by attacking - the b5-bishop comes under fire. } 6. Nxe5 { White uses tactics to grab the pawn back immediately, as taking the bishop loses the queen to Nxc6 (just like we saw in the 'Sense Of Danger' game). } 6... Be7 { However, White is unable to put more pressure down the e-file in time, because first he must deal with the attack on his b5-bishop. After White retreats the bishop, Black will soon castle, with a solid position. (Advanced - See the next two moves for an illustration of this point). } 7. Bf1 Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O) 5... exd4 { This is a mistake, as compared to the 5.Re1 note, the e-file is now completely open, making the pin much more dangerous. } (5... Nd6 { Advanced - This is again the correct move. Instead of trying to keep the extra pawn, Black returns it (much like we saw in 'How To Meet Gambits') to consolidate his position. } 6. Bxc6 { Not the only move, but the most common - White resolves the threat to his bishop by exchanging and buying himself time to regain his pawn. } 6... dxc6 { Black recaptures away from the centre again, to develop his queenside more actively. } 7. dxe5 { White correctly recaptures with the pawn, to gain a tempo on the d6-knight and also increase his space advantage. } 7... Nf5 { This is the most stable square from the knight - it could easily end up trapped or at the very least offside on b5, c4 or e4. } 8. Qxd8+ { White exchanges queens, depriving Black of the right to castle. } 8... Kxd8 { This is the famous 'Berlin Endgame'. This is not the place to analyze or explain it in detail, but we can say that Black's strong bishop pair (specifically, the unopposed light-squared bishop) fully compensates for White's kingside majority and faster development. }) 6. Re1 { This is a thematic reply, pinning the knight and forcing Black to defend with a pawn. } 6... d5 { Black defends the knight while preparing development. However, the new tactical problem is that the knight on c6 is now pinned to the king - the b5-bishop has come to life! } 7. Nxd4 { White regains one of the pawns, and introduces new threats in Nxc6, winning material, and f3, winning the knight on e4.
In fact, Black must now find a very clever tactic just to stay in the game.
(The rest of this game falls under 'Advanced'). } 7... Bd6 { Black can't deal with White's threats anymore, so he tries creating some threats of his own. The next moves will take some effort to understand, but doing so will greatly improve your tactical vision: } (7... Bd7 { This is the most natural defence, breaking the pin, but after } 8. Bxc6 { (avoiding any complications with ...Nxd4, discovering an attack on the b5-bishop) } 8... bxc6 9. f3 { , Black loses the e4-knight by force due to the pin. The extra knight proves sufficient for White to win the game. }) 8. Nxc6 { White follows through on his threat, and takes the knight. } 8... Bxh2+ { Black sacrifices the bishop, in the hope of achieving a draw by perpetual check. } (8... bxc6 9. Bxc6+ { would not be playable for Black, as the king and rook are forked. Even worse, the d5-pawn is about to fall, and with it, the e4-knight. } { [%cal Gc6e8,Gc6a8] }) 9. Kh1 { A very difficult move to find, as one must see two things in advance:
1. 9...Nxf2 is illegal, because of the pin from the e1-rook
2. 9...Qh4 looks like a crushing attack on White's king, but can be met by a strong deflection tactic. } 9... Qh4 { This would be winning for Black (based on ...Bg3 discovered checks) if White didn't have the next two moves. } 10. Rxe4+ { The point of this exchange sacrifice becomes clear in a couple of moves. } 10... dxe4 { Black takes with the pawn, as recapturing with the queen would have left the h2-bishop en prise. } (10... Qxe4 11. Kxh2) 11. Qd8+ { Now it all becomes clear. White needed to clear the d5-pawn out of the way, so that he could deflect the Black queen away from White's king and from the defence of the h2-bishop.
Obviously it wouldn't be fair to expect a beginning player to find all these moves for White in a quick game. Nonetheless, such variations give us a taste of the great beauty and depth of chess, and show that there's always room to discover more in chess (even for Grandmasters). } 11... Qxd8 12. Nxd8+ { Check! } 12... Kxd8 13. Kxh2 { Even this endgame is far from simple - after all, on material, it may appear that Black has a slight material advantage, with a rook and two pawns versus White's knight and bishop.
However, White is actually much better, for a few reasons:
1. He has a lead in development that will increase with moves like Nc3, Bc4, Bf4 and Rd1.
2. Black's king is stuck in the centre, and even though the queens have been traded, White has enough pieces to cause some headaches.
3. Black's pawns are somewhat exposed to attack. For instance, it is not so easy to defend the e4-pawn, as ...f5 here would run into Bg5 checkmate!
This is the longest and most complicated variation in our Study. However, you can easily avoid it by playing 5.Re1. } *


