{ I've covered all the key general opening principles to know, and you're ready to test out the ideas I've shared with you in your own games.

However, there may be some positions where you get stuck, and don't know how you should develop your pieces.

To help you with this, I'll show you two 'System Openings' that can get you into the game quickly.

Our first one is with 1.d4. }
1. d4 { I believe most beginners will improve more quickly if they master 1.e4 first.
However, I include this as an alternative, in case you're really struggling with 1.e4. } 1... d5 { The most common reply, matching White in the centre. } (1... Nf6 { This is Black's most common move at higher levels of play, and forms a set of openings known as the 'Indian' Defences, where Black postpones or even avoids the move ...d5. However, the London System can still be played by White: } 2. Nf3 g6 { This Kingside Fianchetto setup is known as the 'King's Indian', at least when Black follows up with ...d6 later. } 3. Bf4 { The London System is characterized by White developing his bishop to f4 at an early stage.
You may notice that it is very much like the Italian Game from before, only a 'queenside' version.
(The next moves are 'Advanced' and for illustration.) } 3... Bg7 4. e3 O-O { [%csl Gd3] } 5. Be2 { When Black plays ...g6, the White bishop is often better on e2 than d3. } (5. Bd3 { Here the bishop is banging its head on a brick wall, as the g6-pawn is already defended twice.
There's also the risk that a later ...d6 and ...e5-e4 will fork the bishop and f3-knight, which would be unpleasant, to say the least. } { [%csl Gg6][%cal Gd3g6,Gf7g6,Gh7g6] }) 5... d6 { Black opts for a dark-squared strategy and bluntens the range of the f4-bishop, as the d6-pawn is defended twice. } { [%csl Gd6][%cal Ge7d6,Gc7d6] } 6. h3 { With this prophylactic move, White is able to keep his 'London' bishop on f4 alive, as ...Nh5 can now be met by Bh2. This is a thematic idea in the London System, though sometimes White can successfully avoid it altogether. } { [%csl Gh2][%cal Gf6h5,Gf4h2] } (6. O-O Nh5 { This attack on the bishop is what I want to avoid with 6.h3, although this is quite an advanced point. }) 6... Nbd7 { Black has many other possible setups - I use this developing move just for illustration. } 7. O-O { Depending on Black's setup, White can choose between a more aggressive setup with c4/Nc3 (my preference), or a more solid approach with c3/Nbd2. } { [%csl Gc3,Gd2][%cal Gc2c4,Gb1c3] }) 2. Nf3 { White develops his knight solidly, moving a step closer to kingside castling. } (2. c4 { (Advanced - This is the Queen's Gambit, and the most common move. I'll show you how to counter this as Black in the next game.) }) 2... Nf6 { Black follows suit. Other moves can be met in the same way. } 3. Bf4 { The starting position of the London System. By developing his bishop actively on f4 (much like a 'Queenside Italian Game'), he exerts early piece pressure and prepares to develop his kingside pieces, without impeding the activity of his other pieces.
We will see in a later game that this setup can also be employed, in a modified version, as Black. } (3. e3 { This is not a bad move either, but notice how the c1-bishop is suddenly stuck behind the pawn chain - a problem which doesn't arise in the London. } { [%cal Gc1e3] }) 3... e6 { Black has a lot of possible setups, but in each case White's developing moves will be quite similar, with only minor alterations. } 4. e3 { Now we see why it is more harmonious to play 3.Bf4 and only then 4.e3 - now the bishop is actively placed on f4, rather than stuck inside the pawn chain on c1. } { [%csl Gf4,Gc1][%cal Ge2e3] } 4... c5 { Black challenges the White centre with his pawn, much like we saw with the Queen's Gambit on move 2 (2.c4). } 5. Nbd2 { White develops his knight to d2, rather than c3, because he wants to play c2-c3 later to build a nice 'triangle' of pawns from b2 to d4 to f2, overprotecting the d4 strongpoint. } 5... Nc6 { Black, in turn, increases the pressure against the d4-pawn while developing his knight to its most active square. } 6. c3 { White has set up a strong pawn triangle, and his queenside minor pieces are all developed. The next step now is to bring out the kingside pieces with moves like Bd3 and 0-0.
White can also often launch an attack on Black's king when they castle short, starting with moves like Ne5. This e5-knight is White's main bulwark for launching a kingside attack with the pieces. For example: } { [%csl Gb2,Gc3,Gd4,Ge3,Gf2] } 6... Be7 7. Ne5 { This is a great square for the knight, and also avoids problems with ...Nh5, harrassing our strong London bishop on f4. } { [%csl Gh5,Ge5][%cal Gd1h5] } 7... O-O { Castling is natural but somewhat risky here, as White can quickly build up a strong attack. } 8. Bd3 { From here, White can several attacking possibilities - from Qf3-h3 to a kingside pawn storm - or he can simply castle short with the more active position.
To learn how to play the London System like a Grandmaster, and win many more of your White games, check out my Grandmasterclass here: https://members.illingworthchessacademy.com/offers/tM5agbGS } { [%csl Gh7][%cal Gd1f3,Gf3h3,Gg2g5,Gh2h5] } *


